2.3. Advanced Data Structures¶

Module M-227-04: Programming for Data Analytics

Instructor: prof. Dmitry Pavlyuk

Advanced Data Structures¶

  • Graph is a data structure, storing a set of objects (vertices) in which some pairs of the objects are in some sense "related" (connected with edges.
  • Tree is an undirected graph in which any two vertices are connected by exactly one path
  • Forest is a disjoint union of trees

Implemented in Python libraries

Graph¶

  • Graph is a data structure, storing a set of objects (vertices) in which some pairs of the objects are in some sense "related" (connected with edges.

Graph: important types¶

  • Directed vs. Undirected
  • Weighted vs. Unweighted
  • Connected vs. Disconnected
  • Planar vs. Non-planar

Graph: important problems¶

  • Shortest path
  • Connectivity
  • Travelling salesman
  • Minimum spanning tree
  • Maximum network flow

Tree¶

  • Tree is an undirected graph in which any two vertices are connected by exactly one path

Tree: important applications¶

  • Storing hierachies (biological, organisational, etc.)
  • Decision trees in Machine Learning
  • Fast search and insert of data (e.g., database indexing)

Forest¶

  • Forest is a disjoint union of trees

Forest: important application¶

  • Random forest in machine learning is an ensemble learning method for classification, regression and other tasks that operates by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time.

Useful Libraries¶

  • NetworkX https://networkx.org/ - a Python library for the manipulation of the structure, dynamics, and functions of complex networks.
  • igraph https://igraph.org/ - a C library for complex network analysis and graph theory, with emphasis on efficiency, portability and ease of use. Support C/C++, Python, R, Mathematica

Thank you¶
